They seem to be all over the sequence

I will try to smooth the series by calculating window statistics with a window size of apx. 2% of entire series. Checking for moving window statistics

moving_avg <- rollapply(data=ts,width=10000,FUN=mean,align="right")
moving_median <- rollapply(data=ts,width=10000,FUN=median,align="right")
moving_variance <- rollapply(data=ts,width=10000,FUN=var,align="right")

The graph clearly shows how the moving average is affected by the outliers and the population density is still near the zero value as shown by the moving median.

Also there seems to be no clear trend here.

plot.ts(moving_variance)

This shows that the average and variance of the time series is very volatile and changing with time.

Let us perform a Dickey-Fuller Test to check if the series is stationary or not

adf.test(ts,alternative = "stationary")
## Warning in adf.test(ts, alternative = "stationary"): p-value smaller than
## printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  ts
## Dickey-Fuller = -79.896, Lag order = 80, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

The null hypothesis of the series being non-stationary can thus be rejected. Looks like there is no need of differencing

Checking for auto correlations

Acf(ts)

Pacf(ts)

The scale of y axis shows that there is very little (around 0.015) autocorrelation present in the series.

Let us try to fit an arma(p,q) model to this series. Using BIC minimizing strategy to include some penalty for complex models. To reduce overfitting.

final.bic <- Inf
final.order <- c(0,0,0)
for(p in 1:4) for(q in 1:4)
{
  arimafit <- arima(ts,order=c(p,0,q))
  current.bic <- BIC(arimafit)
  if(current.bic < final.bic){
    final.bic <- current.bic
    final.order <- c(p,0,q)
    final.arima <- arima(ts,final.order)
  }
  
}
final.arima

Checking for ARCH effects.

ArchTest(ts)
## 
##  ARCH LM-test; Null hypothesis: no ARCH effects
## 
## data:  ts
## Chi-squared = 35128, df = 12, p-value < 2.2e-16

Based on the p-value we can reject the null hypothesis of no ARCH effects. In other words there are significant ARCH effects in the sequence.

This heteroskedasticity make it really hard to make point estimates for the time sequence data.

Next let us try to fit a GARCH (Generalized Autoregressive Conditional Heteroskedasticity) model to this data in order to fit the volaitility in this data.

Fitting a GARCH model

For the sequencing probabilities, let us try to fit a decision tree on 5 lag variables with the original time series being the dependent variable.

As I am interested in just the sign of the sequences and not the magnitude, I will convert the series to just represent the signs (+ve,-ve or 0) for the numbers.

seqDS <- data.frame(original_ts=ts,
                    lag_1=c(-99999,lag(ts,1)[1:length(ts)-1]),
                    lag_2=c(-9999,-9999,lag(ts,2)[1:(length(ts)-2)]),
                    lag_3=c(-9999,-9999,-9999,lag(ts,3)[1:(length(ts)-3)]),
                    lag_4=c(-9999,-9999,-9999,-9999,lag(ts,4)[1:(length(ts)-4)]),
                    lag_5=c(-9999,-9999,-9999,-9999,-9999,lag(ts,5)[1:(length(ts)-5)]))
head(seqDS,10)

c1 <- ifelse(seqDS$original_ts==0,0,ifelse(seqDS$original_ts>0,"+ve","-ve"))
c2 <- ifelse(seqDS$lag_1==0,"0",ifelse(seqDS$lag_1>0,"+ve","-ve"))
c3 <- ifelse(seqDS$lag_2==0,"0",ifelse(seqDS$lag_2>0,"+ve","-ve"))
c4 <- ifelse(seqDS$lag_3==0,"0",ifelse(seqDS$lag_3>0,"+ve","-ve"))
c5 <- ifelse(seqDS$lag_4==0,"0",ifelse(seqDS$lag_4>0,"+ve","-ve"))
c6 <- ifelse(seqDS$lag_5==0,"0",ifelse(seqDS$lag_5>0,"+ve","-ve"))

seq <- data.frame(cbind(c1,c2,c3,c4,c5,c6))
head(seq)
##    c1  c2  c3  c4  c5  c6
## 1 -ve -ve -ve -ve -ve -ve
## 2 +ve -ve -ve -ve -ve -ve
## 3 +ve +ve -ve -ve -ve -ve
## 4 -ve +ve +ve -ve -ve -ve
## 5 -ve -ve +ve +ve -ve -ve
## 6   0 -ve -ve +ve +ve -ve

Fitting a decision tree onto this data

tree <- rpart(c1~.,data=seq[-c(1:5),],control=rpart.control(minsplit=2, minbucket=1,cp=0.0001))

Plotting the decision rules from the tree

rpart.plot(tree)

From the root node it looks like that the proportion of +ve , -ve and zero values are quite similar in the series. The most significant sequence seems to be for the one for consecutive zeroes. The +ves and the -ves seem to go in a similar sequnce depending upon if the lagged number i-2 != 0 and then break down on whether the i-2 number was +ve or -ve, but the probabilities of that split for both +ve and -ve numbers are less than 50%.

But there seems to be a very significant sequence based on if i-2=0,i-3=0 and i-4=0 then i=0.

plotcp(tree)

The decision tree doesn’t seem to be overfitting the data, so I am content with the sequencing probabilities identified above.

Business Analysis and Creativity

Promo to Subscription prediction model

This model could be built upon historical data regarding previous marketing campaigns to identify customers’ features/ characteristics who are more likey to subcribe.

External data sources:

  • Social Media Data: Data regarding social media activity, marital status,educational background, brand consciousness etc. can be obtained from social media aggregators. This data can be really useful in segmenting the customers according to these features and predict the likelihood to subscribe based on the historical data.

  • Occupational Data: Data regarding what the customers do for a living could potentially determine the economic status of consumers. This sort of data can be obtained from websites like Linkedin, Glassdoor etc.

  • Location Data:Geo Location data about these customers can be utilized in order to identify local retail wine stores and brands which could be our potential competitors.

Some other measures that could be taken in order to make the campagn more effective:

  • Loyality points: Loyality points can be provided to customers for each purchase. These loyality points could then be redeemed by the customers for discounts on subsequent purchases.

  • Customer Quizzes: Customer wine taste can be identified based on personality quizzes.

  • Free delivery over a certain amount of order: The delivery package can also include sampler wines to try. If the customers like it, then they can add it to their preference list in their profiles.
